					<div class="post-content post-single-content">
						
						<input class="jpibfi" type="hidden"><p class="c7"><span class="c3">Have you ever tried to photograph waterfalls and been disappointed with the results? Do you want to know how to capture that silky-smooth look on the water with your camera? Youve come to the right place because we have plenty of useful, (yet simple) waterfall photography tips for you to try out.</span></p>
<h3>1. Capture Motion with a Slow Shutter Speed</h3>
<figure id="attachment_881018" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-881018" style="width: 1600px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden size-full wp-image-881018" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-750x500.jpg" alt="long exposure waterfall" width="700" height="467" data-lazy-srcset="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall.jpg 1600w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-800x534.jpg 800w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-750x500.jpg 750w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-585x390.jpg 585w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-525x350.jpg 525w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-400x267.jpg 400w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-306x204.jpg 306w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-200x133.jpg 200w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-100x67.jpg 100w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" data-jpibfi-post-excerpt="" data-jpibfi-post-url="https://www.slrlounge.com/7-waterfall-photography-tips-to-expand-your-creative-vision/" data-jpibfi-post-title="7 Waterfall Photography Tips to Expand Your Creative Vision" data-jpibfi-src="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-750x500.jpg" ><noscript><img class="size-full wp-image-881018" src="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-750x500.jpg" alt="long exposure waterfall" width="700" height="467" srcset="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall.jpg 1600w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-800x534.jpg 800w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-750x500.jpg 750w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-585x390.jpg 585w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-525x350.jpg 525w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-400x267.jpg 400w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-306x204.jpg 306w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-200x133.jpg 200w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-100x67.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" data-jpibfi-post-excerpt="" data-jpibfi-post-url="https://www.slrlounge.com/7-waterfall-photography-tips-to-expand-your-creative-vision/" data-jpibfi-post-title="7 Waterfall Photography Tips to Expand Your Creative Vision" data-jpibfi-src="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/long-exposure-waterfall-750x500.jpg" ></noscript><figcaption id="caption-attachment-881018" class="wp-caption-text"> Lin and Jirsa Photography</figcaption></figure>
<p>The first of our waterfall photography tips focuses on shutter speed. Because each waterfall is different, and the lighting around it is different, there is no &#8220;one-size-fits-all&#8221; shutter speed. If you want to capture the movement of the water, then you will need to use a slow shutter speed &#8211; usually anything from 1/30th second right up to several seconds &#8211; depending on the natural light around the waterfall and how fast the water is flowing.</p>
<p>Try starting with a 1-second shutter speed, and review your image on the camera. If the water isnt silky-looking enough for your creative vision, then try 1.5 seconds, then 2 seconds, and so on until you get the water looking how you want.</p>
<p>You will need a good, sturdy tripod to shoot at such low shutter speeds, as it will hold the camera steady while the shutter is open. Dont worry if your image looks overexposed at this point, as the next one of our waterfall photography tips looks at fixing that problem.</p>
<h3 class="c7"><span class="c5">2. Get the Correct Exposure</span></h3>
<figure id="attachment_881016" aria-describedby="caption-attachment-881016" style="width: 1600px" class="wp-caption aligncenter"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden size-full wp-image-881016" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-750x500.jpg" alt="waterfall exposure" width="700" height="467" data-lazy-srcset="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure.jpg 1600w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-800x534.jpg 800w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-750x500.jpg 750w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-585x390.jpg 585w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-525x350.jpg 525w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-400x267.jpg 400w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-306x204.jpg 306w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-200x133.jpg 200w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-100x67.jpg 100w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" data-jpibfi-post-excerpt="" data-jpibfi-post-url="https://www.slrlounge.com/7-waterfall-photography-tips-to-expand-your-creative-vision/" data-jpibfi-post-title="7 Waterfall Photography Tips to Expand Your Creative Vision" data-jpibfi-src="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-750x500.jpg" ><noscript><img class="size-full wp-image-881016" src="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-750x500.jpg" alt="waterfall exposure" width="700" height="467" srcset="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure.jpg 1600w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-800x534.jpg 800w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-750x500.jpg 750w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-585x390.jpg 585w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-525x350.jpg 525w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-400x267.jpg 400w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-306x204.jpg 306w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-200x133.jpg 200w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-100x67.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" data-jpibfi-post-excerpt="" data-jpibfi-post-url="https://www.slrlounge.com/7-waterfall-photography-tips-to-expand-your-creative-vision/" data-jpibfi-post-title="7 Waterfall Photography Tips to Expand Your Creative Vision" data-jpibfi-src="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-exposure-750x500.jpg" ></noscript><figcaption id="caption-attachment-881016" class="wp-caption-text"> Lin and Jirsa Photography</figcaption></figure>
<p class="c7"><span class="c3">Because your slow shutter speeds let more light into the camera for a longer period, it can overexpose the rest of your photo, especially if youre shooting in sunlight. </span></p>
<p class="c7"><span class="c3">Follow these general rules of thumb:</span></p>
<ul>
<li class="c7"><span class="c3">As mentioned in the previous tip, s</span><span class="c3">tart with a shutter speed of 1 second and adjust up and down to get the amount of motion blur in the water that you&#8217;re going for.</span></li>
<li class="c7"><span class="c3">Bring your ISO down as low as it will go to reduce the camera sensitivity to light and to maximize the image quality. </span></li>
<li class="c7"><span class="c3"> Then adjust your aperture accordingly to get to your desired exposure. In the day time, you&#8217;ll likely be close to your </span><span class="c3">lens maximum aperture (usually from f/16 to f/32). In darker scenes, you&#8217;ll likely be around f/8; and at night, you&#8217;ll might be wide open.</span></li>
</ul>
<p>For more information, we recommend you brush up on your <a href="https://www.slrlounge.com/workshop/exposure-triangle/">exposure triangle</a>.</p>
<p class="c7"><span class="c3">You may find that these steps just arent enough to correct any overexposure, but dont worry as our next waterfall photography tip is on using lens filters to reduce exposure even more.</span></p>
<h3 class="c7"><span class="c5">3. Use Lens Filters</span></h3>
<p class="c7"><span class="c3"><img class="lazy lazy-hidden aligncenter size-full wp-image-877853" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-800x484.jpg" alt="nd filter for shutter drag" width="700" height="424" data-lazy-srcset="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag.jpg 1920w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-826x500.jpg 826w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-800x484.jpg 800w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-585x354.jpg 585w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-578x350.jpg 578w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-400x242.jpg 400w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-337x204.jpg 337w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-200x121.jpg 200w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-1600x968.jpg 1600w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-100x61.jpg 100w" data-lazy-sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" data-jpibfi-post-excerpt="" data-jpibfi-post-url="https://www.slrlounge.com/7-waterfall-photography-tips-to-expand-your-creative-vision/" data-jpibfi-post-title="7 Waterfall Photography Tips to Expand Your Creative Vision" data-jpibfi-src="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-800x484.jpg" ><noscript><img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-877853" src="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-800x484.jpg" alt="nd filter for shutter drag" width="700" height="424" srcset="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag.jpg 1920w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-826x500.jpg 826w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-800x484.jpg 800w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-585x354.jpg 585w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-578x350.jpg 578w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-400x242.jpg 400w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-337x204.jpg 337w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-200x121.jpg 200w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-1600x968.jpg 1600w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-100x61.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" data-jpibfi-post-excerpt="" data-jpibfi-post-url="https://www.slrlounge.com/7-waterfall-photography-tips-to-expand-your-creative-vision/" data-jpibfi-post-title="7 Waterfall Photography Tips to Expand Your Creative Vision" data-jpibfi-src="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/07/nd-filter-for-shutter-drag-800x484.jpg" ></noscript></span></p>
<p class="c7"><span class="c3">Filters are made of different strengths of dark glass that are circular and screw on the filter thread at the front of the lens, or are rectangular and go into a special holder so that they cover the front of the lens. High quality <a href="https://www.slrlounge.com/glossary/neutral-density-filter-definition/">ND (Neutral Density) filters</a> are very useful for landscape and nature photographers, as they reduce the amount of light coming into the camera without changing the colors in the image. You can also use a polarizing filter that cuts down the light and also reduces reflections from water and rocks etc. while increasing the saturation to give your image a more vivid look.</span></p>
<h3 class="c7"><span class="c5">4. Pick the Right Time of Day to Shoot</span></h3>
