et="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-photography-tutorial.jpg 1600w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-photography-tutorial-800x534.jpg 800w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-photography-tutorial-750x500.jpg 750w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-photography-tutorial-585x390.jpg 585w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-photography-tutorial-525x350.jpg 525w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-photography-tutorial-400x267.jpg 400w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-photography-tutorial-306x204.jpg 306w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-photography-tutorial-200x133.jpg 200w, https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-photography-tutorial-100x67.jpg 100w" sizes="(max-width: 700px) 100vw, 700px" data-jpibfi-post-excerpt="" data-jpibfi-post-url="https://www.slrlounge.com/7-waterfall-photography-tips-to-expand-your-creative-vision/" data-jpibfi-post-title="7 Waterfall Photography Tips to Expand Your Creative Vision" data-jpibfi-src="https://www.slrlounge.com/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/waterfall-photography-tutorial-750x500.jpg" ></noscript><figcaption id="caption-attachment-881014" class="wp-caption-text"> Lin and Jirsa Photography</figcaption></figure>
<p class="c7"><span class="c3">The next in our series of essential waterfall photography tips is to pick the right time of day to shoot. Bright, midday sun can make it very difficult to get the correct exposure, so the best idea is to shoot in an hour or so after sunrise, or the hour before sunset if you can.</span></p>
<p class="c7"><span class="c3">Shooting at these times of the day or in overcast weather will give you a much better chance of getting even exposure without annoying sun reflections in the water.</span></p>
