<p><img class="lazy lazy-hidden" title="" src="data:image/gif;base64,R0lGODlhAQABAIAAAAAAAP///yH5BAEAAAAALAAAAAABAAEAAAIBRAA7" data-lazy-type="image" data-lazy-src="images/image4.jpg" alt="" data-jpibfi-post-excerpt="" data-jpibfi-post-url="https://www.slrlounge.com/7-waterfall-photography-tips-to-expand-your-creative-vision/" data-jpibfi-post-title="7 Waterfall Photography Tips to Expand Your Creative Vision" data-jpibfi-src="images/image4.jpg" ><noscript><img title="" src="images/image4.jpg" alt="" data-jpibfi-post-excerpt="" data-jpibfi-post-url="https://www.slrlounge.com/7-waterfall-photography-tips-to-expand-your-creative-vision/" data-jpibfi-post-title="7 Waterfall Photography Tips to Expand Your Creative Vision" data-jpibfi-src="images/image4.jpg" ></noscript><span class="c3">Have you ever noticed how most folks shoot waterfalls in portrait orientation? It does make sense because waterfalls are usually thin and long, but you can get some stunning landscape orientation shots of waterfalls that stand out from the crowd. Shooting this way will probably seem strange at first but it does push you out of your comfort zone and makes you more creative.</span></p>
